Notes:

Date: 0/9/1958
Source: Tararua
Author:
Vol / Page: 26
Edition:
Quote: If any word originating in the mountain clubs deserves to be incorporated in the language it is perhaps scroggin. That mixture of raisins, sultanas, chocolate, nuts, boiled lollies, a mixture of bits and pieces of whatever one fancies, was evolved to fill the need for a sustaining, palatable, easily-carried food, one as readily available for a bite snatched in a cold, wet, momentary halt as for a welcome spell in the warmth and sun. The word seems to come from Otago but its derivation is not clear. There is a Scotch and North of England dialect word scrog which refers to stunted bushes, and if some Otago Scot had this in mind it prompts dark thoughts as to what the original comestible may have been like. Perhaps it is one of those words that have no known ancestry, that come out of the blue, such as children sometimes so happily coin.
Notes: 1958 Sep Ruth Mason `Track and Trail' in Tararua 26

Date: 7/1/1980
Source: NZ Woman's Weekly
Author:
Vol / Page: 83/2
Edition:
Quote: SCROGEN 1 cup peanuts 3/4 cup dried apricots 1 + 135 gram block energy chocolate 1/2 cup mixed dried fruit 1/4 cup sunflower seeds 1/2 cup coconut 2 tablespoons powdered glucose. Roast the peanuts at 180 degrees C for 10-15 minutes, or until lightly golden. Cool. Chop the apricots and chocolate coarsely. In a strong plastic bag, put the penuts, apricots, chocolate, mixed fruit, sunflower seeds, coconut and glucose. Shake to combine. Secure closed. Use as a high energy snack food. Makes about 4 cups.
